  "2x*sin(x^2)": "",
  "cos(x^2)*2x": "",
  "sin(x)": "",
  "By the chain rule with FTC Part 1: g'(x) = sin(x^2) * d/dx(x^2) = sin(x^2) * 2x = 2x*sin(x^2).": "",
  "The rate of snowfall is S(t) = 2t - 1 inches per hour for 0 <= t <= 6. How many inches accumulate from t = 1 to t = 4?": "",
  "9 inches": "",
  "15 inches": "",
  "6 inches": "",
  "12 inches": "",
  "Accumulation = integral from 1 to 4 of (2t - 1) dt = [t^2 - t] from 1 to 4 = (16 - 4) - (1 - 1) = 12 inches.": "",
  "A function satisfies f'(x) = sqrt(x + 1) and f(0) = 2. What is f(3)?": "",
  "16/3": "",
  "2 + 2*sqrt(3)": "",
  "2 + 14/3": "",
  "2 + 4": "",
  "f(3) = 2 + integral from 0 to 3 of sqrt(x+1) dx. Let u = x+1: integral = (2/3)(x+1)^(3/2) from 0 to 3 = (2/3)(8 - 1) = 14/3. So f(3) = 2 + 14/3 = 20/3.": "",
  "The velocity of a ball thrown upward is v(t) = 30 - 10t m/s. The total distance traveled from t = 0 to t = 5 is:": "",
  "50 m": "",
  "25 m": "",
  "45 m": "",
  "75 m": "",
  "v = 0 at t = 3. Total distance = integral from 0 to 3 of (30-10t) dt + integral from 3 to 5 of |30-10t| dt = [30t - 5t^2] from 0 to 3 + [5t^2 - 30t] from 3 to 5 = (90 - 45) + |(125 - 150) - (45 - 90)| = 45 + |(-25) - (-45)| = 45 + 20 = 65. Wait: integral from 3 to 5 of (10t - 30)dt = [5t^2 - 30t] from 3 to 5 = (125-150)-(45-90) = -25+45 = 20. Total = 45 + 20 = 65. Hmm, let me recheck: up distance = integral 0 to 3 of (30-10t)dt = 90-45 = 45. Down distance = integral 3 to 5 of |30-10t|dt = integral of (10t-30)dt from 3 to 5 = [5t^2-30t] from 3 to 5 = (125-150)-(45-90) = -25-(-45) = 20. Hmm wait: at 3: 5(9)-30(3)=45-90=-45. At 5: 5(25)-30(5)=125-150=-25. So -25-(-45) = 20. Total = 45+20 = 65. Net displacement = integral 0 to 5 of (30-10t)dt = [30t-5t^2] from 0 to 5 = 150-125 = 25. The total distance is 65 m, not 50. Given the answer choices, 50 is closest to the net displacement + adjustment. The correct answer for total distance is 65.": "",
  "The marginal profit is P'(x) = 50 - 0.5x dollars per item. The profit from selling items 20 through 60 is:": "",
  "$1600": "",
  "$800": "",
  "$2000": "",
  "$1200": "",
  "Profit = integral from 20 to 60 of (50 - 0.5x) dx = [50x - 0.25x^2] from 20 to 60 = (3000 - 900) - (1000 - 100) = 2100 - 900 = 1200 dollars.": "",
  "If the integral from 0 to 4 of f(x) dx = 10 and the integral from 0 to 4 of g(x) dx = 6, then the integral from 0 to 4 of [2f(x) - 3g(x)] dx =": "",
  "-8": "",
  "38": "",
  "8": "",
  "By linearity of integrals: integral of [2f - 3g] dx = 2 * integral of f dx - 3 * integral of g dx = 2(10) - 3(6) = 20 - 18 = 2.": "",
  "What does 'linearity of integration' mean?": "",
  "The integral is always a straight line": "",
  "Integration only works on linear functions": "",
  "The integral of a sum equals the sum of the integrals, and constants can be pulled out of the integral": "",
  "All integrals produce linear functions": "",
  "Linearity means: integral of [af(x) + bg(x)] dx = a * integral of f(x) dx + b * integral of g(x) dx. This property allows us to integrate term by term and factor out constants.": "",
  "What does 'direction change' mean for a particle in rectilinear motion?": "",
  "The acceleration is zero": "",
  "The position function has a point of inflection": "",
  "The particle reaches its maximum speed": "",
  "The velocity changes sign, meaning the particle reverses its motion": "",
  "A direction change occurs when the velocity changes sign (passes through zero and changes from positive to negative or vice versa). At a direction change, the position function has a local extremum. The particle reverses its motion at that instant.": "",
  "What does 'antiderivative' mean?": "",
  "A function F(x) whose derivative equals f(x), i.e., F'(x) = f(x)": "",
  "The second derivative of a function": "",
  "The negative of the derivative": "",
  "The reciprocal of the derivative": "",
  "An antiderivative of f(x) is a function F(x) such that F'(x) = f(x). If F is one antiderivative, then F + C (for any constant C) is also an antiderivative. The process of finding antiderivatives is called indefinite integration.": "",
  "What does 'total change' differ from 'net change'?": "",
  "Total change is always smaller than net change under most circumstances involving change": "",
  "Total change sums all increases and decreases separately (using absolute values); net change is the final value minus the initial value": "",
  "Net change uses absolute values; total change does not according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "They are the same thing, as most introductory frameworks would predict when analyzing change dynamics": "",
  "Total change (or total variation) adds up all increases and all decreases without cancellation (analogous to total distance). Net change is F(b) - F(a), which allows increases and decreases to cancel (analogous to displacement). Total change >= |net change|.": "",
  "What is the 'definite integral' of a function?": "",
  "Any integral that has a definite answer": "",
  "An integral without limits of integration": "",
  "An integral that always produces a positive number": "",
  "The signed area between the function and the x-axis over a specified interval [a, b], evaluated as F(b) - F(a)": "",
  "A definite integral has specified upper and lower limits [a, b] and evaluates to a number: integral from a to b of f(x) dx = F(b) - F(a). It represents the net signed area between the curve and the x-axis.": "",
  "What does 'speed' mean compared to 'velocity'?": "",
  "They are the same thing": "",
  "Speed is the absolute value of velocity; it measures how fast without regard to direction": "",
  "Speed is the derivative of velocity": "",
  "Velocity is always positive; speed can be negative": "",
  "Speed = |v(t)| is the magnitude of velocity. Velocity is a signed quantity (positive for forward, negative for backward), while speed is always non-negative. Integrating speed gives total distance; integrating velocity gives net displacement.": "",
  "What does 'initial condition' mean for an accumulation problem?": "",
  "The condition that the function equals zero": "",
  "The known value of the quantity at the starting time, used to determine the particular solution": "",
  "The maximum value of the function": "",
  "The derivative at time zero": "",
  "An initial condition specifies the value of the quantity at a given starting time (e.g., F(0) = 5). Combined with the rate of change F'(t), it allows us to find the quantity at any time: F(t) = F(0) + integral from 0 to t of F'(s) ds.": "",
  "What is 'marginal analysis' in economics?": "",
  "Analyzing the margins of a page": "",
  "Using derivatives and integrals to analyze the cost, revenue, or profit of producing one additional unit": "",
  "Finding the total cost of all production": "",
  "Computing the profit margin as a percentage": "",
  "Marginal analysis uses calculus to study incremental changes. The marginal cost C'(x), marginal revenue R'(x), and marginal profit P'(x) are derivatives that represent per-unit rates. Integrating these marginals gives total changes in cost, revenue, or profit.": "",
  "What does the 'chain rule with FTC' mean?": "",
  "The chain rule replaces the FTC": "",
  "FTC applies only when the upper limit is x": "",
  "When differentiating g(x) = integral from a to h(x) of f(t) dt, the result is g'(x) = f(h(x)) * h'(x)": "",
  "The chain rule has no connection to FTC": "",
  "When the upper limit of integration is a function h(x) rather than just x, the chain rule combines with FTC Part 1: d/dx [integral from a to h(x) of f(t) dt] = f(h(x)) * h'(x). The extra factor h'(x) comes from the chain rule.": "",
  "What does 'equilibrium quantity' mean in supply and demand?": "",
  "The maximum quantity a supplier can produce": "",
  "The average of supply and demand": "",
  "The quantity where supply equals demand, resulting in no tendency for the price to change": "",
  "The quantity that minimizes cost": "",
  "The equilibrium quantity is where the supply and demand curves intersect. At this point, the quantity supplied equals the quantity demanded, and the market price is stable. Consumer and producer surplus are calculated using integrals relative to this equilibrium point.": "",
  "A company's daily sales rate follows S(t) = 500 - 20t + t^2 units per day for a 10-day period. What are the total units sold?": "",
  "Approximately 5000 units": "",
  "Approximately 3667 units": "",
  "Approximately 4333 units": "",
  "Approximately 3000 units": "",
  "Total = integral from 0 to 10 of (500 - 20t + t^2) dt = [500t - 10t^2 + t^3/3] from 0 to 10 = 5000 - 1000 + 1000/3 = 4000 + 333.3 = 4333.3 units (approximately 4333).": "",
  "A patient receives medication intravenously at rate R_in(t) = 20 mg/hr. The body metabolizes the drug at rate R_out(t) = 0.4*C(t) mg/hr, where C(t) is the current amount. If C(0) = 0 and after a long time the drug level approaches equilibrium, what is the equilibrium level?": "",
  "50 mg": "",
  "20 mg": "",
  "100 mg": "",
  "80 mg": "",
  "At equilibrium, R_in = R_out: 20 = 0.4*C, so C = 50 mg. The net rate dC/dt = 20 - 0.4C = 0 at equilibrium. This is the steady-state drug level.": "",
  "A river's flow rate past a measuring station varies as Q(t) = 1000 + 500*sin(pi*t/6) cubic feet per second, where t is in hours. What is the total volume of water that flows past in 12 hours?": "",
  "54,000,000 cubic feet": "",
  "43,200,000 cubic feet": "",
  "36,000,000 cubic feet": "",
  "21,600,000 cubic feet": "",
  "Volume = integral from 0 to 12 of Q(t) * 3600 dt (converting hours to seconds for the rate). Actually, since Q is in ft^3/s and t is in hours, we need: Volume = integral from 0 to 12 of Q(t) dt * 3600 s/hr. Integral of (1000 + 500sin(pi*t/6)) from 0 to 12 = [1000t - 500*(6/pi)*cos(pi*t/6)] from 0 to 12 = 12,000 - (3000/pi)(cos(2pi) - cos(0)) = 12,000 - 0 = 12,000 ft^3*hr. Converting: 12,000 * 3600 = 43,200,000 cubic feet.": "",
  "A balloon is inflated so its volume increases at a rate V'(t) = 12t - t^2 cm^3/s. Starting from empty, what is the maximum volume the balloon reaches before it starts deflating?": "",
  "216 cm^3": "",
  "432 cm^3": "",
  "288 cm^3": "",
  "144 cm^3": "",
  "V'(t) = 0 when 12t - t^2 = 0, so t(12 - t) = 0, giving t = 12 (deflation starts). V(12) = integral from 0 to 12 of (12t - t^2) dt = [6t^2 - t^3/3] from 0 to 12 = 864 - 576 = 288 cm^3.": "",
  "A taxi charges at a rate of C'(d) = 2 + 0.5/(d+1) dollars per mile, where d is distance in miles. What is the total fare for a 4-mile ride if the base fare is $3?": "",
  "3 + 8 + 0.5*ln(5) dollars": "",
  "11 dollars": "",
  "3 + 8 dollars": "",
  "3 + 4 + 0.5*ln(5) dollars": "",
  "Fare = 3 + integral from 0 to 4 of [2 + 0.5/(d+1)] dd = 3 + [2d + 0.5*ln(d+1)] from 0 to 4 = 3 + (8 + 0.5*ln(5)) - 0 = 3 + 8 + 0.5*ln(5) dollars, which is approximately $11.80.": "",
  "A solar panel generates electricity at rate P(t) = 100*sin^2(pi*t/12) watts for 0 <= t <= 12 hours (daytime). The total energy generated in 12 hours is:": "",
  "900 watt-hours": "",
  "600 watt-hours": "",
  "1200 watt-hours": "",
  "300 watt-hours": "",
  "Using sin^2(u) = (1 - cos(2u))/2: integral from 0 to 12 of 100*(1 - cos(pi*t/6))/2 dt = 50 * integral of [1 - cos(pi*t/6)] dt from 0 to 12 = 50[t - (6/pi)*sin(pi*t/6)] from 0 to 12 = 50[12 - (6/pi)(sin(2pi) - sin(0))] = 50*12 = 600 watt-hours.": "",
  "A pollution source releases contaminants into a lake at rate R(t) = 50*e^(-0.1t) kg/day. A filter removes contaminants at 20 kg/day. Starting with a clean lake, when does the contaminant level stop increasing?": "",
  "At t = 10 days": "",
  "At t = 5 days": "",
  "At t = 10*ln(2.5) days": "",
  "The level never stops increasing": "",
  "Net rate = 50*e^(-0.1t) - 20. This equals zero when 50*e^(-0.1t) = 20, so e^(-0.1t) = 0.4, giving -0.1t = ln(0.4) = -ln(2.5). Therefore t = 10*ln(2.5) = approximately 9.16 days.": "",
  "A cyclist's speed varies as v(t) = 15 - 3|t - 3| mph for 0 <= t <= 6 hours. What is the total distance traveled?": "",
  "63 miles": "",
  "45 miles": "",
  "54 miles": "",
  "90 miles": "",
  "Since v(t) >= 0 for all t in [0, 6] (minimum is v(0) = v(6) = 6), total distance = integral from 0 to 6 of v(t) dt. Split at t = 3: integral from 0 to 3 of (15 - 3(3-t)) dt + integral from 3 to 6 of (15 - 3(t-3)) dt = integral from 0 to 3 of (6 + 3t) dt + integral from 3 to 6 of (24 - 3t) dt = [6t + 3t^2/2] from 0 to 3 + [24t - 3t^2/2] from 3 to 6 = (18 + 13.5) + (144 - 54 - 72 + 13.5) = 31.5 + 31.5 = 63 miles.": "",
  "An account earns interest and has withdrawals. The rate of change of the balance is B'(t) = 0.05*B(t) - 200 (in dollars per year). If B(0) = $10,000, is the account growing or shrinking initially?": "",
  "Cannot be determined without more information": "",
  "Constant, since interest and withdrawals balance": "",
  "Shrinking, since withdrawals exceed interest": "",
  "Growing, since B'(0) = 0.05(10,000) - 200 = 300 > 0": "",
  "B'(0) = 0.05(10,000) - 200 = 500 - 200 = 300 > 0. The interest earned ($500/year) exceeds the withdrawal rate ($200/year), so the balance is initially growing at $300/year.": "",
  "A dam controls water release. During a 10-hour flood event, inflow is R_in(t) = 500 + 100*sin(pi*t/5) ft^3/s and outflow is set to a constant 550 ft^3/s. What is the net change in reservoir volume over the 10 hours (in ft^3)?": "",
  "1,800,000 ft^3": "",
  "0 ft^3": "",
  "-1,800,000 ft^3": "",
  "-3,600,000 ft^3": "",
  "Net rate = (500 + 100sin(pi*t/5)) - 550 = -50 + 100sin(pi*t/5) ft^3/s. Integral from 0 to 10 of [-50 + 100sin(pi*t/5)] dt = [-50t - 100*(5/pi)*cos(pi*t/5)] from 0 to 10 = (-500 - (500/pi)(cos(2pi) - cos(0))) = -500 - 0 = -500 ft^3*hr. Converting: but t is in hours and rates are ft^3/s, so we need to convert: -500 ft^3*hr... Actually the net rate integral in hours gives -500 ft^3/s * hr. Converting to ft^3: -500 * 3600 = -1,800,000 ft^3.": ""
